{{Infobox Encyclical | name = ''Dominum et vivificantem'' | language = Latin | translation = The Lord and Giver of Life | argument = On the Holy Spirit in the life of the Catholic Church and the world. | date = 18 May 1986 | pope = John Paul II | papal_coat_of_arms = John paul 2 coa.svg | pages = | number = 5 of 14 | before = ''[[Slavorum Apostoli]]'' | after = ''[[Redemptoris Mater]]'' | web_en = http://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_18051986_dominum-et-vivificantem_en.html | web_la = https://web.archive.org/web/20130703222848/http://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_18051986_dominum-et-vivificantem_lt.html }} {{italic title}} '''''Dominum et vivificantem''''' (Latin: ''The Lord and Giver of Life'') is the fifth [[encyclical]] written by [[Pope John Paul II]]. The encyclical was [[promulgated]] on 18 May 1986. It is a theological examination of the role of the [[Holy Spirit]] as it pertains to the modern world and the church and the use of spiritual [[Prayer_in_the_Catholic_Church|prayer]] to renew one's spiritual life.
In 1986, Pope John Paul II was already anticipating the new millennium, with its new challenges, as well as the new [[Grace_in_Christianity|graces]] the Holy Spirit would bestow upon the [[Catholic Church|Church]] as she celebrated the [[Great Jubilee]] beginning the third millennium of [[Christianity]]. Wishing to prepare the Church for these things by giving the people of God an increased awareness and knowledge of the Holy Spirit, he issued the encyclical on May 18, the Solemnity of [[Pentecost]].<ref>Convincing the World:St. John Paul's Encyclical on the Holy Spirit, https://www.catholicculture.org/commentary/otc.cfm?id=1317, 2015 [retrieved 2018.04.04]</ref>
