'''Michael Marder''' is [[Ikerbasque]] Research Professor of Philosophy at [[the University of the Basque Country]], [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ikerbasque.net/michael.marder|title=Michael Marder at IKERBASQUE}},</ref> He works in the phenomenological tradition of [[Continental philosophy]], environmental thought, and [[political philosophy]].

==Education==
Marder studied at universities in Canada and the U.S. He received his PhD in Philosophy at the [[New School for Social Research]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/event-of-the-thing-on-post-deconstructive-realism/oclc/479267051|title=New School PhD Dissertation|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> Marder carried out post-doctoral research in the Department of Philosophy at the [[University of Toronto]], and taught at [[Georgetown University]], [[George Washington University]], and [[St. Thomas More College]] at the [[University of Saskatchewan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcnallyrobinson.com/event-9098/Michael-Marder#.UqrJS79EzIM|title=Michael Marder (reading and signing)}}</ref>

==Career==
Marder carried out research in [[phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenology]] as an FCT fellow at the [[University of Lisbon]], Portugal, and held the position of Assistant Professor in the Department of Philosophy at [[Duquesne University]] in [[Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Department News| url=http://www.duq.edu/Documents/philosophy/_pdf/philosophy_newsletterVol3Issue1.pdf|work=Duquesne Graduate Philosophy News|date=2010|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> before accepting the [[Ikerbasque]] research professorship at the [[University of the Basque Country]].<ref>[http://www.ikerbasque.net/michael.marder Michael Marder faculty page at Ikerbasque, the Basque Foundation for Science]</ref>

Marder is an editorial associate of the Journal [[Telos (journal)|Telos]] (New York)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telospress.com|title=About the Editor|publisher=Telos|date=2014|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> and an editor of four book series: "Political Theory and Contemporary Philosophy" Series,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/series/political-theory-and-contemporary-philosophy/|title=Bloomsbury - Political Theory and Contemporary Philosophy|publisher=Bloomsbury|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> "Critical Plant Studies",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodopi.nl/senj.asp?SerieId=PLANT|title=Critical Plant Studies: Philosophy, Literature, Culture|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> "Future Perfect: Images of the Time to Come in Philosophy, Politics, and Cultural Studies",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rowmaninternational.com/series/future-perfect-images-of-the-time-to-come-in-philosophy-politics-and-cultural-studies|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield International|title=Future Perfect: Images of the Time to Come in Philosophy, Politics and Cultural Studies|accessdate=25 October 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025044513/http://www.rowmaninternational.com/series/future-perfect-images-of-the-time-to-come-in-philosophy-politics-and-cultural-studies|archivedate=25 October 2014|df=}}</ref> and "Palgrave Studies in Postmetaphysical Thought.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/palgrave-studies-in-postmetaphysical-thought-michael-marder/?K=9781137328731|title=Palgrave Studies in Postmetaphysical Thought|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>

Much of his philosophical work has focused on building philosophies that take into account plants as beings with their own form of [[subjectivity]], which has included showing how the field of philosophy, especially the tradition of [[continental philosophy]], has neglected plants or treated them as "[[Other (philosophy)|other]]", and how the field has been poorer for it.<ref name=Pettman>{{cite news |last1=Pettman |first1=Dominic |title=The Noble Cabbage: Michael Marder’s "Plant-Thinking"|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-noble-cabbage-michael-marders-plant-thinking/#! |work=Los Angeles Review of Books |date=July 28, 2013}}</ref> Dominic Pettman found Marder's book ''Plant-Thinking'' to be a work that made a substantial contribution to that nascent field, but also at times too simplistic, for example idealizing the ways that plants co-exist with other beings and not taking into account the ways that plants attack and defend against other beings.<ref name=Pettman/>

