'''Miguel Jerónimo Larreinaga y Silva''' (September 29, 1772 &ndash; April 28, 1847) was a [[Nicaraguan]] [[philosopher]], humanist, [[lawyer]] and [[poet]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Ramón |last=Juárez Salazar |title=Telica cumple 130 años de ser municipio |url=http://archivo.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2001/mayo/14-mayo-2001/departamentos/departamentos4.html |work=El Nuevo Diario |accessdate=2008-01-17 |language=Spanish |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717185716/http://archivo.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2001/mayo/14-mayo-2001/departamentos/departamentos4.html |archivedate=2011-07-17 |df= }}</ref> He was one of the people who traveled to [[Spain]] in 1818 to ask for independence of the Central American Republic, which was granted to [[Nicaragua]] and four other countries in 1821. He is depicted on the obverse of the current C$10 [[Nicaraguan córdoba|Córdoba]] note in Nicaragua.<ref>{{cite news| first=| last=| coauthors=| title=Nicaraguan Money: C$10| date=| publisher=| url=http://www.vianica.com/money.php?type=banknotes&value=10| work=ViaNica| pages=| accessdate=2008-01-17| language=| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503095853/http://www.vianica.com/money.php?type=banknotes&value=10| archivedate=2008-05-03| df=}}</ref>
Miguel Larreinaga was born in [[León, Nicaragua|León]], Nicaragua. His father was Joaquín Larreinaga, who was [[Spanish people|Spanish]] and died before his birth, and his mother was Manuela Balmaceda y Silva who died in childbirth. His paternal grandfather adopted and educated him.<ref>{{cite news | first=Carlos | last=Tünnermann Bernheim | title=Breve biografía del prócer Licenciado Miguel Larreinaga | url=http://archivo.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2001/septiembre/15-septiembre-2001/cultural/cultural2.html | work=El Nuevo Diario | accessdate=2008-01-17 | language=Spanish | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221203150/http://archivo.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2001/septiembre/15-septiembre-2001/cultural/cultural2.html | archivedate=2007-12-21 | df= }}</ref>
Larreinaga died on April 20, 1847. His remains are buried under the floor of [[Our Lady of Grace Cathedral, León]].
