{{England-bio-stub}}

'''Robert Kirk''' is an  [[emeritus]] [[professor]] in the Department of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Nottingham]].  He is known for his work on [[philosophical zombies]]&mdash;putatively unconscious beings physically and behaviourally identical to human beings.  Although Kirk did not invent this idea, he introduced the term ''zombie'' in his 1974 papers "Sentience and Behaviour"<ref>{{cite journal |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Sentience and Behaviour |journal=Mind |volume=83 |issue=329 |pages=43–60 |date=January 1974 |jstor=2252795 |doi=10.1093/mind/lxxxiii.329.43}}</ref> and "Zombies v. Materialists".<ref>{{cite journal |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Zombies v. Materialists |journal=Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society |volume=48 |issue=Suppl |pages=135–152 |year=1974}}</ref> In the latter he offered a formulation of [[physicalism]] that aimed to make clear that if zombies are possible, physicalism is false: an argument that was not much noticed until David Chalmers's development of it in ''The Conscious Mind''.<ref>{{cite book |first=David |last=Chalmers |title=The Conscious Mind: in Search of a Fundamental Theory |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1996 |isbn= }}</ref> Kirk himself had reversed his position earlier,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=From Physical Explicability to Full-blooded Materialism |journal=Philosophical Quarterly|volume=29 |pages=229–37 |date=1979 |doi=10.2307/2218819}}</ref> and has argued against the zombie idea in a number of books and articles on physicalism and consciousness.<ref>{{cite book |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Raw feeling: a philosophical account of the essence of consciousness |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1994 |isbn= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Zombies and Consciousness |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2005 |isbn=0-19-928548-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=The Inconceivability of Zombies |journal=Philosophical Studies|volume=39 |pages=73–98 |date=2008 |doi=10.1007/s11098-007-9103-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=The Conceptual Link from Physical to Mental |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2013 |isbn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Robots, Zombies and Us |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2017 |isbn=}}</ref>

As well as working on other topics in the philosophy of mind, Kirk has published on the question of how far translation and interpretation are determined by objective facts (see W. V. Quine’s ''Word and Object'' (1960)). His own book on this topic, ''Translation Determined'',<ref>{{cite book |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Translation Determined |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1986 |isbn=}}</ref> appeared in 1986. Another main interest is relativism.<ref>{{cite book |authormask=1 |first=Robert |last=Kirk |title=Relativism and Reality |publisher=Routledge |year=1999 |isbn=}}</ref>

